reviewText: This is one of the dumbest Sci Fi comedies I've ever seen. I can laugh at slapstick and silly jokes but this wasn't even funny ever. This could have been a really great comedy but the jokes got old after about 4 minutes and seemed like they were the same jokes over and over and mostly vulgar. Can anybody make a comedy today without resorting to being vulgar? Seemed like this movie was just thrown together to capitalize on Pegg's recent popularity. Well not so popular anymore. If you watch the trailer then you'll see ALL the funny parts, seriously that is all there is. If you like really dumb, stupid and vulgar comedy then you will certainly enjoy this movie. If on the other hand you are looking for real comedy then skip this movie.

reviewText: If Jon Stewart is Gen-X's Walter Cronkite, Simon Pegg and Nick Frost are its Laurel and Hardy. With the comedy "Paul," the writing and acting duo try to do for sci-fi movies what they did for zombie flicks (Shaun of the Dead) and buddy cop pictures (Hot Fuzz): simultaneously skewer and pay homage to the genres' tropes.After a brief preamble featuring a very surprised golden retriever, Paul flash forwards to modern-day Comic-Con, where we meet our British heroes, Graeme (Pegg) and Clive (Frost), the kind of overage fanboys who swoon for chicks in Princess Leia bikinis and debate the literary merits of fictional sci-fi author Adam Shadowchild (Jeffrey Tambor) in both English and Klingon. After a couple of perfect days in Nerd Heaven, the guys take off on a cross-country tour of extraterrestrial hot spots and wind up having a real-life close encounter with a weed-toking alien named Paul (voiced by Seth Rogan), who's just escaped from a top-secret military base.After 60-odd years, Paul, who favors cargo shorts, has apparently outlived his usefulness and is about to have his brain dissected by the federal government. Weaving a complex tapestry of profanity and reason, Paul convinces the guys to help him evade the ominous Agent Zoil (Jason Bateman) and his boss, The Big Guy (Sigourney Weaver). Along the way, Graeme also picks up a one-eyed religious zealot played by Kristen Wiig, who finds her Christian fundamentalism seriously undermined by the existence of extraterrestrial life.The movie, directed by Greg Mottola (Superbad), is filled with dozens of clever references to classic sci-fi fare, the best featuring a cameo by Steven Spielberg himself. And as all of the Pegg-Frost movies do, Paul had me in stitches a couple of times -- I'll never look at a bagel again without smiling. But I suspect that the geekier the audience the greater the laughs. I can't wait for Pegg and Frost's take on Harry Potter.The so-so DVD extras for Paul include an extended version that adds little to the theatrical version, bloopers, feature commentary, and several shots of Pegg making funny faces during filming.  Review originally posted on MyDVDInsider.com.
summary: "E.T." and other sci-fi flicks skewered by Pegg and Frost
